    "narrative": "Today\u2019s offensive engine is anchored by **Austin Riley** (72.43) and **James Wood** (71.27), both of whom clear the 70-point threshold thanks to favorable matchups against mediocre arms. **Austin Riley** benefits immensely from the +19% boost provided by the SP skill projection of Irvin, J, and while the catcher\u2019s arm strength is a slight negative, his presence in the cleanup spot keeps his floor high. Meanwhile, **James Wood** is our most efficient play for speed-related upside; leading off against Elder presents an ideal environment for him to exploit the bases, as the +10% order bonus aligns perfectly with the favorable park factors. **Tyler Soderstrom** also earns a strong recommendation at 68.84, buoyed by a robust platoon advantage against Hancock that offsets the park\u2019s pitcher-friendly profile.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was **Kyle Karros**, who flirted with the lineup but ultimately finished at 44.69. While the park factors and platoon advantage were enticing, the combination of his #8 spot in the order and the efficiency of **Vinnie Pasquantino** (58.38) and **Dalton Rushing** (54.29) made him the clear odd man out to preserve game caps. We are proceeding with caution regarding **Max Muncy** and **Tyler Soderstrom**, as both remain \"Lineup Pending.\" While we have modeled them under the assumption of their expected spots, any deviation in the batting order or a late scratch could necessitate a pivot to our available depth. **Vinnie Pasquantino** remains a \"Strong\" start despite a tough draw against Bradish, as the wind blowing out and his dynamic platoon splits provide enough cushion to keep him in the 1B slot ahead of riskier, lower-upside bench options like **Kyle Karros**.",
